  "response_text": "At first, a row of translucent orange prescription pill bottles stretches diagonally into darkness. Their caps look dark green under the lighting, and the bottles sit beside a set of evenly spaced, stair-like green ridges. The lighting is dramatic and clinical, with a deep green cast and strong shadows. The bottles appear in perspective, with one large bottle close to the left foreground and several smaller ones receding toward the upper right, all filled with reddish-orange pills.\n\nThe prescription bottles then appear arranged upright across a dark, glossy surface, backlit so their amber plastic glows. They vary in height and cap colour, with some black, white, or greenish caps. The pills inside are visible as soft, rounded shapes through the plastic. The background remains a dark green-black gradient, giving the display a laboratory or pharmacy-like atmosphere.\n\nA hand enters visually through the close-up composition, holding one amber prescription bottle in front of the others. Only fingertips are visible at the top edges of the bottle. The bottle’s white label fills the screen, marked with a large “Rx” at the upper left and a horizontal prescription line across the label. Later, black text appears on the label beneath the “Rx,” reading: “82% OF DOCTORS SURVEYED HAVE PRESCRIBED ORUDIS.” A soft green circular glow highlights the wording, drawing attention to the statistic.\n\nThe imagery shifts into an abstract green space. Bright green beams radiate from the center like light shining through a tunnel. Yellow-green letter shapes emerge through the glow, then the scene flares to a nearly white-yellow flash. As the brightness settles, a round green tablet or sphere appears centered against a green background. Across its face, in bold dark lettering, is the product name “ORUDIS KT.” Small white safety text appears along the bottom: “Use as directed. If allergic to any pain reliever, consult a doctor before use.” The green Orudis KT sphere hovers for a moment over a softly lit surface, casting a shadow below, then slowly lowers until it rests on the green floor.\n\nThe product is then visually compared with another round tablet behind it. In front is the larger green “ORUDIS KT” sphere, and behind it sits a white round tablet labeled “Motrin IB.” Near the white tablet is the text “400 mg,” while near the Orudis KT sphere the text reads “Just 25 mg.” The layout places the green Orudis KT tablet prominently in the foreground, with the white comparison tablet partly behind it.\n\nAdditional comparison imagery briefly layers in, with ghosted medicine packaging and dosage numbers appearing around the tablets. The visible numbers include “1000 mg,” “440 mg,” “400 mg,” and “Just 25 mg,” suggesting a side-by-side dosage comparison while the green Orudis KT sphere remains the main foreground object.\n\nFinally, the actual Orudis KT retail packages are displayed on a glossy dark surface against the same green backdrop. Two boxes sit angled toward the viewer. The left box is green with large yellow “ORUDIS” lettering and “KT” beside it; it is labeled “tablets,” and the smaller text includes “Ketoprofen tablets 12.5 mg.” A red strip along the top reads “NEW! NOW IN NONPRESCRIPTION STRENGTH.” The right box is a darker green package with large white “ORUDIS KT” lettering and “caplets,” also showing “Ketoprofen tablets 12.5 mg” and pain reliever wording. The boxes remain side by side, cleanly lit, with their reflections faintly visible on the surface beneath them.",
